<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-02T09:49:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-02T09:49:00-05:00" n="555" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d555">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.51/359.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-02T10:00:00-04:49">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 2, 1914, 10 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Department’s November 27, 5 p.m., I had an interview with Minister
                            for Foreign Affairs last evening and endeavored to discourage the issue
                            of paper currency and strongly advocated your views. Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs said this issue would not dispose of financial question
                            to be taken up in Washington on arrival of the commission, but as the
                            bank had refused any assistance and the Government unable to place a
                            loan and without funds it was compelled to take this course to meet
                            pressing immediate needs.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Blanchard</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>